<br>
The Iksar beastlord stared at the notice in some dismay.  &quot;By Thule, who put my name down there?&quot;<br>
<br>
He looked accusingly at his warder, but the scaled wolf looked blankly back at him, its long, pointed tongue lolling.  No answer.<br>
<br>
Mudfish sighed and took himself to the nearest scribe to dictate a letter.  (His command of Human was getting better, but he still wasn't certain of it.)<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE HR START--><hr /><!--EZCODE HR END--><br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em><br>
My esteemed lord,<br>
<br>
I regret to inform you that it was never my intention to enter the bard's contest in Freeport, as tempting as it is, as I am not sure I will be available to travel to Freeport on that day.  I am afraid I would not be an adequate contestant in any case.<br>
<br>
Thank you for the compliment, however.<br>
<br>
Your humble servant,<br>
Mudfish<br>
</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
The Vah Shir scribe read back the letter in the Iksar's native Lizardman and looked up expectantly.  Mudfish frowned.  &quot;That's not how I said it.  Is all that flowery flattery necessary?&quot;  He wondered if it sounded as horrendously awkward in Human as it did in Lizardman.<br>
<br>
The scribe nodded emphatically.  &quot;Oh, yes.  Otherwise, the man will most be insulted, yes.  This way keeps the fur smooth.&quot;<br>
<br>
Mudfish sighed.  &quot;Oh, fine, fine.  Send it.&quot;  He passed over the required fee and headed out of Shar Vahl. <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><br>
